        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Oct 18<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Once again I have to thank you for all the trouble which I have caused you. It was my simple ignorance: I had always heard of &amp; seen blue litmus paper, &amp; could not believe that it was right.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Yours truly obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9098.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Edward Frankland, 16 October 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had received some sensitive litmus paper from Frankland, and had queried whether it should be pink, or whether it had been exposed to acid in the post (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9098.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Edward Frankland, 16 October 1873</ref> and n. 1). Litmus paper is purple when in a neutral environment.</note>
        </div>        
            
